.)`\n\nThat is the important contrast with [uncommit.rs]([REDACTED:path]), which uses `materialize_without_checkout()` to preserve removed hunks in the worktree.\n\n**Oplog**\nUse `OperationKind::DiscardChanges`, matching existing destructive discard semantics. One oddity: `commit_uncommit_changes` already uses `DiscardChanges` too, even though it keeps changes in the workspace. I would still use `DiscardChanges` here unless we want to introduce a new operation kind to separate ãuncommit selected changesã from ãdiscard selected committed changesã.\n\n**Result Type**\nIãd return existing `MoveChangesResult`:\n\n```rust\npub struct MoveChangesResult {\n    pub workspace: WorkspaceState,\n}\n```\n\nNo new DTO seems necessary unless the UI needs `discardedCommit` or rejected hunks. The lower-level operation currently bails if any described change cannot be removed, so there is no partial-success payload to expose.\n\n**Tests**\nAdd or mirror tests near [crates/but-workspace/tests/workspace/commit/uncommit_changes.rs]([REDACTED:path]), but the most valuable behavior test may be API-level or rebase-level:\n\n- selected file/hunk is removed from the rewritten commit\n- normal materialization removes the change from disk\n- dry run previews the rewritten workspace without changing refs/worktree\n- conflicted commit behavior matches `uncommit_changes`: currently it bails\n- empty `changes` behavior should be decided; today it likely rewrites as a no-op unless `create_tree_without_diff` rejects it\n\n**Generated/Client Surface**\nAfter adding `#[but_api(napi)]`, run the SDK generation flow per repo instructions:\n\n```sh\npnpm build:sdk\npnpm format\n```\n\nThen wire clients only if needed:\n\n- [packages/but-sdk/src/generated/index.d.ts]([REDACTED:path]) generated\n- `apps/desktop/src/lib/stacks/stackEndpoints.ts` if desktop needs a mutation\n- `apps/lite/electron/src/ipc.ts`, `preload.cts`, `main.ts`, and Lite UI hooks if Lite needs it\n\nMy recommended first pass